agp:AllProvinces.agp:description: About 7850 m of siliciclastic rocks with small amount of basalt, limestone, chert, ironstone, felsic porphyry, and silicic volcanic rocks. Unconformable on Whitewater Violcanics at S end of Range, elsewhere surrounded by Devonian limestones of Canning Basin. Conglomerate in upper units 'appears to be glacigene'.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:comments: Neoproterozoic age assigned from glacigene appearance of some rocks in the group.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:source: Grey, K., Griffin, T.J., 1990. Local sedimentary successions related to the orogens, Geological Survey of Western Australia. Memoir 3

agp:AllProvinces.agp:description: The ?Ordovician to Recent Exmouth sub-basin is one of the main depocentres of the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains over 12km of predominantly siliciclastics marine and nonmarine sediments
agp:AllProvinces.agp:overview: The mostly offshore, ?Ordovician to Recent Exmouth Sub-basin is the southernmost part of the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains over 12,000 m of predominantly marine and non-marine siliciclastics. The sub-basin is bounded to the northeast by the Alpha Arch, to the southeast by the Rough Range Fault, and to the south by the Bernier Platform. The Carnarvon Basin originated as an intracratonic fracture basin during Silurian rifting, which later evolved into an interior sag basin during the Devonian and Carboniferous. Carboniferous and Permian sedimentation was influenced by glacial conditions, but the return to warmer climatic conditions allowed deposition of extensive fluvio-deltaic to shallow marine sediments. The pre-rift Triassic succession comprises marine shale overlain by fluvio-deltaic sediments, which were in turn overlain by shallow marine sediments. Subsequent Early Jurassic rifting led to the development of the Exmouth Sub-basin and deposition of a thick Lower to Upper Jurassic succession of marine sediments. Uplift and erosion to the south provided a sediment source for Lower Cretaceous marine sandstones which prograded across the sub-basin. Seafloor spreading to the south limited sediment sourcing, and a subsequent structural inversion caused crestal erosion along highs and provided a source for another succession of marine sandstones. A major marine transgression in the Hauterivian marked the beginning of the post-rift phase with deposition of extensive marine shales through most of the Cretaceous, although these are thin in the southern part of the sub-basin. Late Cretaceous to Neogene sedimentation occurred under stable passive margin conditions with extensive deposition of marine carbonates. Since exploration commenced in 1947, 16 hydrocarbon accumulations (oil and gas) have been discovered (Dec 2001). Sandstones of the Lower Cretaceous Barrow Group are the primary reservoirs in the sub-basin. The main play types include faulted anticlines, tilted fault blocks and stratigraphic pinch-outs, with regional seal formed by Lower to Upper Cretaceous marine shales and siltstones. Upper Jurassic marine shales form the principal hydrocarbon source.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:source: Tindale, K., Newell, N., Keall, J., Smith, N., 1998. Structural evolution and charge history of the Exmouth Sub-basin, northern Carnarvon Basin, Western Australia, in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. (eds), The sedimentary basins of Western Australia 2. Pr*

agp:AllProvinces.agp:description: The Mitakoodi Domain is comprised of volcanic and sedimentary rocks of the Leichhardt Superbasin; no basement is exposed, and younger rocks are not present. No signficant intrusions are present. The domains has been affected by the Gun (Late Calvert) extensional event and by all four Isan Orogenies.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:comments: Youngest isotopic date in domain is 40Ar-39Ar mica date of 1400 +/- 5 Ma
agp:AllProvinces.agp:overview: The Mitakookd Domains is a belt of volcanic and sedimentary rocks of Leichhardt Superbasin in middle of the Mount Isa Orogen. No basement is exposed. The succession begins with silicic Bulonga Volcanics at ~1760 Ma, but may contain silicic volcanics of lithologically similar Argylla Formation (not dated in Mitakoodi Domain); if so, sequence would start at 1790-1780 Ma. The volcanics are overlain by the mafic Marraba Volcanics (with some siliciclastic beds) and then by the Mitakoodi Quartzite, with a depositional age of 1755 Ma. Bedding in the Mitakoodi is inverted on the west limb of the Bulonga Anticline, dipping moderately to gently to the east (20 deg but facing downward) near the western boundary of the domain. The Overhang Jaspilite is the top unit, and is composed mostly of argillaceous rocks and limestone with a small amount of jaspilite. A breccia unit, the Chumvale Breccia, is a ferruginous weathering profile on brecciated vein-fillings and fault breccias in the Overhang Jaspilite; the profile comprises fragments and masses of quartz, commonly showing growth laminae (indicating deposition in faults and open veins) in a matrix of iron oxide + fractured quartz grains to clasts (A.J.Stewart field observations 1988; GA field notebook 139, pp.99-110). No significant intrusions are present in the domain. The domain has been affected by the 1690-1670 Ma Gun (Later Calvert Superbasin) extensional event and by the Early (1600-1580 ma). Middle (1570-1550 Ma), Mid (1550-1540 Ma), and Late (1530-1500 Ma) Isan Orogenies.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:source: Geological Survey of Queensland, 2011. North-West Queensland mineral and energy province report and data package, Queensland Department of Employment, Economic Development and Innovation 1v

agp:AllProvinces.agp:description: Paleo- to Mesozoic orogen formed at a convergent continental margin. Has fault slices of Neoproterozoic (Marlborough Province) to Early Cambrian (Peel-Manning Fault System) from basement , but the oldest 'new' rocks are Mid-Cambrian volcanics and siliciclastics in the Murrawong area, NSW. The main sedt-volc sequence began in the mid-Silurian and ended in the Late Permian (refid 68822, fig. 3). Activity ended with the Hunter-Bowen Orogeny (Early Permian to Late Triassic). AJS
agp:AllProvinces.agp:comments: Maxage is from volcaniclastics and argillite in Murrawong area of NSW (refid 68822, fig. 3 and p.329, para 2) . Minage taken as end of Hunter-Bowen Orogeny, which deformed the New England Orogen (refid 68667, p.307). u72185=AJS
agp:AllProvinces.agp:overview: New South Wales (summarised from refid 68822: Glen 2013, AJES 60, 315-370, by u72185 = AJStewart 12 Sep 2013). Oldest rocks are Mid-Cambrian supra-subduction mafic-intermediate volcaniclastics and argillite, overlain by siliciclastics. Unconformably overlain by Mid-Ordovician siliciclastics and limestone. Other Ordovician occurrences are allochthonous: mafic volcanics in serpentinite, volcaniclastics and chert, blueschist, and limestone. Main sequence began at ~433 Ma, in the Gamilaroi and Hastings provinces, where volcaniclastic and mafic to silicic volcs and limestone accumulated, and went on to the Mid (Gamilaroi) and Late Devonian (W Hastings). The Hunter-Bowen Supercycle (refid 68822) of 4 cycles of W-dipping subduction from ~370-230 Ma then followed. Cycle 1, ~370-365 Ma: formation of Baldwin Arc; kilometre-long blocks of andesite mark arc-forearc basin boundary, and pass E into arc-sourced, forearc basin sedts (Tamworth Trough) and thence E to subduction complexes. Arc volcanism ceased ~308-305 Ma. Cycle 2, 365-305 Ma: 1) Formation of andesite and dacite of Currabubula Arc (above the Baldwin Arc) at continental margin facing E. The two arcs could be one arc that changed composition through time, from (mafic)-intermediate to silicic (refid 68822, p.338). Latest Carboniferous deformation ended the cycle. Cycle 3, 305-264 Ma: Early Permian rift or transtensional basins (Sydney and Gunnedah basins, preceded by tholeiite) unconformable on Cycle 2. Early Permian exhumation exposed older serpentinite in the Peel-Manning Fault System, and S and I granites intruded from ~300 to ~265 Ma. The early volcanics range from alkali within-plate through MORB type to ocean-floor tholeiite, indicating eruption into a progressively widening backarc basin behind a plate boundary rolling back to the E (refid 68822, p. 338). Oroclinal bending folded and doubled the width of the region, and ceased at ~264 Ma. Cycle 4, 264-230 Ma: Continental margin subduction resumed, and lasted to Late Triassic. The subduction produced arc to backarc-derived granites and related volcanics in the Middle and Late Permian. Deformation succeeded the granites, and migrated W as part of a foreland-propagating fold thrust belt. Middle to Late Triassic contraction ended the Cycle. Queensland (summarised from refid 68667, Jell et al 2013, Geology of Queensland, by u72185 = AJStewart, 12 Sep 2013). As in NSW, the Orogen is a mid to late Paleozoic rock assemblage formed by convergent tectonics at a continental margin. (A small fault block of Ordovician rocks S of Gladstone may be an allochthonous block or fault sliver.) The oldest rocks of the volcano-sedimentary sequence are Late Silurian, and are exposed in fault blocks and inliers collectively called the Calliope Province, scattered through the Yarrol Province. The oldest rocks in the Orogen are serpentinite fault slices dated at 562 +/- 22 Ma in the Marlborough Province, and are pieces of basement thrustfaulted into the Orogen in the Late Permian. The Orogen comprises six provinces. Calliope Province: fault blocks and inliers of volcaniclastics, siliciclastics, mafic-silicic volcs, and limestone, interpreted as remnants of older oceanic island arcs that were accreted to the continental margin during E-dipping subduction by the end of the Devonian. Wandilla Province: blocks of Late Devonian-Carboniferous rocks and melange, interpreted as accretionary wedge above a W-dipping subduction zone; deformed in Late Permian. Yarrol Province: thick Devonian-Carboniferous forearc basin volcaniclastics, mafic-felsic volcs, limestone, non-marine siliciclastics. Connors-Auburn Province: Carboniferous-Permian felsic volcanics and granites above W-dipping subduction zone. Marlborough Province: faulted-in Neoproterozoic-Paleozoic serpentinite and metasedts from basement. Gympie Province: marine Triassic rocks and mafic-intermediate volcanics and limestone; related to Bowen Basin. All deformed by Hunter-Bowen Orogeny.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:source: Glen, R.A., 2013. Refining accretionary orogen models for the Tasmanides of eastern Australia, Australian Journal of Earth Sciences 60(3)

agp:AllProvinces.agp:description: The Charters Towers Province comprises late Neoproterozoic to early Paleozoic metamorphic rocks (largely metasedments and minor mafic rocks: Cape River, Argentine, Charters Towers and Running River metamorphics), Ordovician sedimentary and volcanic rocks (Seventy Mile Range Group), and largely non-marine sedimentary rocks of the Burdekin Basin. These rocks were intruded by the Macrossan, Pama and Kennedy igneous associations. Mineral deposits include Charters Towers (Au) and Thalanga (Cu-Zn-Pb).
agp:AllProvinces.agp:comments: Maximum age is that of the Buckland Hill Diorite, which is the oldest reliable age. The host Charters Towers Metamorphics must be older. The youngest ages are from the Kennedy Igneous Association, the youngest phase of which has an age of 290-260 Ma.
agp:AllProvinces.agp:overview: The Charters Towers extends from the coast around Townsville approximately 150 km inland. It is bound to the north by the Broken River Province, and the Etheridge Province to the west. In the southwest and southeast the province is overlain by the Galilee and Drummond basins, respectively. The oldest unit in the province is the Cape River Metamorphics, which is constrained between ~950 Ma and ~493 Ma by a maximum depositional age and the crystallisation age of the Fat Hen Creek Complex. The Cape River Metamorphics, which are present in the western part of the province, are dominated by quartz-rich metasedimentary schist and gneiss (sandstone and mudstone protoliths), with lesser quartzite, calc-silicate rock, graphitic schist and amphibolite. The amphibolite is associated with banded iron formation and has tholeiitic affinity. A probable correlate of the Cape River Metamorphics, based on lithological similarities and limited geochronological constraints, is the Charters Towers Metamorphics, which occur as rafts within the Ravenswood Batholith. This unit is characterised by pelitic and psammitic metasedimentary rocks with minor calc-silicate rock and amphibolite, and have been metamorphosed to amphibolite grade at low pressure (garnet absent). The Charters Towers Metamorphics were intruded by the Bucklands Hill Diorite, which has an emplacement age of ~508 Ma, providing a minimum age constraint on the Charters Towers Metamorphics. This diorite has an epsilon Nd value of -0.1 (at 508 Ma), indicating a relatively juvenile source. The Argentine Metamorphics, located in the northern part of the province, are characterised by two packages with different metamorphic grades. The lower grade (upper greenschist-amphibolite) package consists of two units, a mixed package of mica schist and quartzite, and a mafic-rich package with amphibolite, mafic schist, chlorite schist, calc-silicate rocks and marble. The higher grade (amphibolite) package contains metasedimentary schist, paragneiss, leucogranite, quartzite, orthogneiss, mica schist, amphobolite and phyllite. The mafic rocks have tholeiitic affinities. The Argentine Metamorphics are constrained in age between ~500 Ma (maximum depositional age) and ~480 Ma (crystallisation age of the intrusive Ravenswood Granodiorite Complex). The Running River Metamorphics, located in the northern part of the province, consist of biotite gneiss, migmatite, amphibolite, mica schist and quartzite, a similar assemblage to the higher grade Argentine Metamorphics. These rocks occur as a screen in the Carboniferous Oweenee Batholith. The Seventy Mile Range Group consists of sandstone/siltstone with numerous mafic dykes (Puddler Creek Formation), overlain by rhyolitic to dacite lavas and associated volcaniclastic rocks (Mount Windsor Volcanics), felsic to intermediate volcanic rocks and turbidites (Trooper Creek Formation) and volcaniclastic siltstone and sandstone (Rollston Range Formation). A felsic rocks from the Mount Windsor Volcanics yielded a SHRIMP age of ~479 Ma, and a graptolite from the uppermost part of the Rollston Range Formation indicates a probable Darriwilian (~466 Ma) age. The Burdekin Basin overlies these rocks in the eastern part of the province and contains Emsian (~407 Ma) to Tournasian (~345 Ma) siliciclastic rocks with minor limestone and volcanic rocks. The Charters Towers Province was intruded by granites of the Macrossan (Fat Hen Complex [~493 Ma] and parts of the Ravenswood Batholith [~490-482 Ma]), the Pama (parts of the Ravenswood and Lolworth Batholiths: 420-400 Ma), and the Kennedy (Oweenee Supersuite [345-330 Ma], Leichhardt Supersuite [310-283 Ma], and Woodstock Supersuite [285-265 Ma]) igneous associations. The Charters Towers Province includes serveral mineral deposits: volcanic-hosted massive sulfide (e.g., Thalanga, Reward, Liontown and Waterloo), lode gold deposits (e.g., Charters Towers, and Ravenswood) and intrusion-related gold deposits (e.g., Mount Leyshon).
agp:AllProvinces.agp:source: Ferguson, C.L., Henderson, R.A., Hutton, L.J., Withnall, I.W., 2013. Charters Towers Province, In Jell, P. A. (Editor), 2013. Geology of Queensland, Geological Survey of Queensland Chapter 3.3
